~ Recognizer of Handwritten Digits ~¶

Abstract:¶

The aim of this noteboook is to create an automatic handwritten recognizer. In order to achieve this goal, some deep learning techniques will be exploited along with a very popular open source dataset: EMNIST (Extended Modified National Institute of Standards and Technology). In particular, a branch of machine learning, known as supervised learning, is used in order to train classifiers able to predict handwritten digits and characters written on papers. So, after a first training, the classifier is jointly applied with some basic computer vision algorithm to print out all characters written on an input image.

Note: The operation of training the model is performed only once. After that, results (weights = variables computed during the optimization process) are saved into 'bin' folder in order to be reused for successive runnings. Due to the nature of the project, it is possible to train classifiers able to recognize only digits or either digits and characters (47 handwritten characters. All uppercase and some lowercase letters). In this notebook, both classifier are used and discussed.

Liberaries:¶

The following libraries are required

  • Tensorflow
  • Keras
  • Sklearn
  • Numpy
  • Matplotlib
  • OpenCV-Python
  • emnist

Leatest versions can be easily installed just running on a shell, in the project folder, the following command:

pip install -r requirements.txt

Note: the previous command installs the tensorflow cpu version. If compatible GPUs are available, consider to install the tensorflow-gpu vesion.

1.0 Import Packages and Custom Classes¶

Note: " init .py" file is used to make available all class files at the package level. Three classes are imported:

  • Dataset
  • Model
  • DigitClassificator

A complete description of available methods can be found in each class documentation.

From 2.0 to 5.0 all three are used and their primarily functions are explained.

In [1]:
import os
from modules import Dataset, Model, DigitClassificator

Using TensorFlow backend.

# create a variable with the path of the project
mainDir = os.path.abspath('.')

2.0 Create a Dataset Object¶

Note: Dataset class downloads only ones the dataset and then it caches (~500 MB) a zip folder in the default .cache folder. Some practical methods are available to inspect the loaded data.

In [3]:
# create an object of the class Dataset
# being  onlyDigits True dataset will download only digits data of the MNIST Original dataset (kerasDB)
dataset = Dataset(mainDir, dirData = 'dataset', onlyDigits=True, kerasDB=True, verbose = False)

3.0 Create two Model Objects - Only Digits and one for Characters¶

Note: Model takes as primarily argument a dataset object. Indeed, the provided instance is exploited in the case of a new train. As default option, model objects try always to load a pre-trained model from the dirBin folder. If not found, it is automatically performed a new training using the specified parameters (hyper-parameters).

In [21]:
# create an object of the class Model
# no forced train and char False ---> load digits weights
model_digits = Model(mainDir, dataset, dirBin = 'bin', char=False, 
              epochs = 20, batchSize = 128, train=False, verbose=True)
In [4]:
# create an object of the class Model
# FORCED train and char True ---> train when characters classifier is launched
model_char = Model(mainDir, dataset, dirBin = 'bin', char=True, 
              epochs = 100, batchSize = 128, train=True, verbose=True)

4.0 Create a Detector Object for Digits Classification¶

Class Notes: DigitClassificator loads a model object and performs the needed operations to properly prepare it for inference. Then two methods are available to predict characters from plain sheets or boxes with a specific dimension.

In [7]:
media = 'media'
In [22]:
# create an object of the class DigitClassificator

clf_digit = DigitClassificator(model_digits, verbose=True)
